Here is an example of using ITextTextRenderer to convert HTML to PDF in Java:

```java
// Import required iText classes
import com.itextpdf.text.Document;
import com.itextpdf.text.DocumentException;
import com.itextpdf.text.pdf.PdfWriter;
import com.itextpdf.tool.xml.XMLWorkerHelper;

// Import ITextTextRenderer 
import com.itextpdf.text.pdf.parser.ITextTextRenderer;

public class HTMLToPDF {

  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

    // Source HTML
    String html = "<html><body><p>Hello World!</p></body></html>";

    // Create PDF document
    Document document = new Document();

    // Create PDF writer
    PdfWriter writer = PdfWriter.getInstance(document, new FileOutputStream("html.pdf"));

    // Open document
    document.open(); 

    // Create ITextTextRenderer 
    ITextTextRenderer renderer = new ITextTextRenderer();
    renderer.setDocument(document);

    // Load HTML
    renderer.setHtmlText(html);

    // Layout and render HTML to PDF
    renderer.layout(); 
    renderer.createPDF(writer);

    // Close document
    document.close();

  }

}
```

The key steps are:

1. Create a new Document 
2. Obtain a PdfWriter instance 
3. Open the Document
4. Create an ITextTextRenderer
5. Set HTML text on renderer 
6. Call layout() to parse the HTML
7. Call createPDF() to render to PDF
8. Close the document

This will take the provided HTML string and convert it to a PDF file using ITextTextRenderer. The renderer handles parsing the HTML and rendering it to PDF format.

