- Override hover/focus states for links and buttons
- Use `!important` to make sure styles override Bootstrap defaults
- Pick a darker blue color like #003366

This will change the primary blue used by Bootstrap for backgrounds, text, buttons etc. to a darker blue. The !important rules force it to override the default Bootstrap CSS.

You can tweak the hex codes to get your desired shade of dark blue. But this shows how to change the primary color in Bootstrap overall.

Here are a few ways to create a div with a curved boundary in Bootstrap:

**Rounded Corners**

Use the `.rounded` utility classes:

```html
<div class="rounded-circle p-5">
  <!-- content -->
</div>
```

`.rounded-circle` makes the div completely circular.

**Border Radius**

Use custom CSS border-radius:

```css
.curved-div {
  border-radius: 50px;
}
``` 

Increase the pixels for more curve.

**SVG Background** 

Use an SVG image for the curve:

```css
.curved-div {
  background-image: url('curved-shape.svg');
}
```

Position the SVG at bottom to act as curve.

**Pseudo-elements**

```css
.curved-div:after {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  width: 100%;
  height: 50px;
  border-radius: 0 0 50px 50px;
  background: white;
}
```

Creates a curved pseudo-element along the bottom.

**Clip Path**

```css
.curved-div {
  clip-path: ellipse(100% 100% at 50% 0%); 
}
```

Clips the div into a curved shape with CSS clip-path.

So in summary, you can curve div borders in Bootstrap with rounded utilities, border-radius, SVG backgrounds, pseudo-elements, and clip paths.

To wrap text within a <span> element in Bootstrap, you can use these approaches:

**max-width**

```css
span {
  max-width: 300px;
}
```

Set a max-width on the <span> to force wrapping.

**word-break**

```css
span {
  word-break: break-word;
}
```

Allows long words to wrap using word-break.

**white-space**

```css
span {
  white-space: normal; 
}
```

The white-space property can force wrapping.

**display: inline-block**

```css
span {
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 300px;
}
```

Make the <span> an inline-block element to wrap.

**Responsive**

```css
@media (max-width: 500px) {
  span {
    max-width: 100%;
  }
}
```

Wrap only on smaller screens using media queries.

**Utility class**

```html
<span class="text-break">...</span>
```

Bootstrap's .text-break class will wrap.

So in summary, the key is using max-width, word-break, white-space, display, or the text-break utility to make text within a <span> wrap in Bootstrap.

Here is an example of making a simple GET request using the Apache HttpClient library and handling closing the client:

```java
import org.apache.http.client.methods.CloseableHttpResponse;
import org.apache.http.client.methods.HttpGet;
import org.apache.http.impl.client.CloseableHttpClient;
import org.apache.http.impl.client.HttpClients;

public class HttpClientExample {

  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {

    CloseableHttpClient httpClient = HttpClients.createDefault();
    HttpGet request = new HttpGet("http://example.com"); 

    CloseableHttpResponse response = httpClient.execute(request);

    // handle response...


    response.close();
    httpClient.close(); 
  }

}
```

The key points are:

- Create a CloseableHttpClient instance 
- Create the HttpGet request
- Execute the request using httpClient
- Close the response with response.close()
- Close the client with httpClient.close()

This ensures the HTTP resources are properly closed after using the client.

For better resource handling, you can wrap the code in try-with-resources blocks:

```java
try (CloseableHttpClient httpClient = HttpClients.createDefault()) {

  // execute request 

} 

```

This will automatically close the client, even if an exception occurs.

Here are a few approaches to update dynamic data in an HTML page before generating a PDF with html2pdf in JavaScript:

**1. Template Literals**

Use template literals to inject data into the HTML:

```js
const data = {
  name: "John",
  date: new Date() 
};

const html = `
  <h1>${data.name}</h1>
  <p>Generated on: ${data.date}</p>
`;

const pdf = html2pdf().from(html).save();
```

**2. DOM Manipulation**

Update elements in the DOM before passing to html2pdf:

```js
const data = {
  name: "Jane"  
};

document.querySelector("#name").innerText = data.name;

const pdf = html2pdf().from(document.documentElement).save();
```

**3. Templating Engine**

Use a template engine like Handlebars to render the HTML:

```js
const source = document.getElementById("template").innerHTML;
const template = Handlebars.compile(source);

const data = {
  name: "Mary"  
};

const html = template(data);

const pdf = html2pdf().from(html).save();
```

**4. Separate Endpoint** 

Make a request to an endpoint that returns updated HTML:

```js
fetch("/generate-pdf")
  .then(res => res.text())
  .then(html => {
    const pdf = html2pdf().from(html).save(); 
  });
```

So in summary, inject data before passing HTML to html2pdf using templates, DOM updates, templating engines or separate endpoints.

