Here is an example of encoding and decoding a string to Base64 in Java:

```java
import java.util.Base64;

public class Base64EncodeDecode {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    String originalString = "Hello World!";

    String encodedString = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(originalString.getBytes());
    System.out.println("Encoded String: " + encodedString);

    byte[] decodedBytes = Base64.getDecoder().decode(encodedString);
    String decodedString = new String(decodedBytes);
    System.out.println("Decoded String: " + decodedString);
  }

}
```

The key steps are:

- Convert the original string to bytes using `String.getBytes()`
- Encode the bytes to Base64 using `Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString()`
- Decode the Base64 string to bytes using `Base64.getDecoder().decode()` 
- Convert bytes back to string using `new String(bytes)`

The encoded string will contain only Base64 characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /) and will be larger than the original string.

Base64 is commonly used to encode binary data into strings that can be safely transmitted over protocols like HTTP that expect text.

Here is an example of how to generate a PDF from a HTML string using openhtmltopdf in Java:

```java
import com.openhtmltopdf.pdfboxout.PdfRendererBuilder;

public class GeneratePdf {

  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {

    String html = "<html><body><p>Hello World</p></body></html>";

    try (OutputStream os = new FileOutputStream("test.pdf")) {

      PdfRendererBuilder builder = new PdfRendererBuilder();

      builder.withHtmlContent(html, "/");

      builder.toStream(os);
      builder.run();
    }
  }
}
```

The key steps are:

1. Create the HTML content as a String

2. Create a PdfRendererBuilder

3. Call builder.withHtmlContent() and pass the HTML string 

4. Set the base URI using "/" if there are no relative resources

5. Call toStream() to output the PDF to an OutputStream 

6. Call run() to render the PDF

7. Close the OutputStream when done

This will generate a PDF containing the provided HTML. You can also load an external CSS file, pass additional options to configure page size, headers/footers etc.

Some other overloads allow passing the HTML as a byte array or from an InputStream as well. But the String version is useful for simple HTML generation cases.

