Here is a complete code example to generate a PDF from HTML using openhtmltopdf with Maven dependencies:

**pom.xml**

```xml
<dependencies>

  <dependency>
    <groupId>com.openhtmltopdf</groupId>
    <artifactId>openhtmltopdf-pdfbox</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.6</version>
  </dependency>

  <dependency>
    <groupId>org.thymeleaf</groupId>
    <artifactId>thymeleaf</artifactId>
    <version>3.0.12.RELEASE</version>
  </dependency>

</dependencies>
```

**HTMLTemplate.html**

```html
<html xmlns:th="http://www.thymeleaf.org">
...
</html> 
```

**PdfGenerator.java**

```java
import com.openhtmltopdf.pdfboxout.PdfRendererBuilder;
import org.thymeleaf.TemplateEngine;
import org.thymeleaf.context.Context;

public class PdfGenerator {

  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {

    TemplateEngine engine = TemplateEngine.create();
    Context context = new Context();

    // populate model 
    context.setVariable("name", "John");

    // generate HTML with Thymeleaf 
    String html = engine.process("HTMLTemplate", context); 

    try (OutputStream os = new FileOutputStream("output.pdf")) {
      PdfRendererBuilder builder = new PdfRendererBuilder();
      builder.withHtmlContent(html, "/");
      builder.toStream(os);
      builder.run();
    }
  }
}  
```

This loads the openhtmltopdf and Thymeleaf dependencies from Maven, uses a Thymeleaf template to generate HTML, and passes it to openhtmltopdf to generate the PDF.

The html and pdf files can be customized as needed.

To change the font when using `PdfRendererBuilder` from the `openhtmltopdf` library in Java, you need to specify the font(s) you want to use for rendering your PDF. This involves adding fonts to the `PdfRendererBuilder` instance with the appropriate methods for font directory, font file, or using a font embedded in a CSS file. Here's how you can do it:

### Using a Font File

If you have a specific font file (e.g., `MyFont.ttf` for Arabic content) that you want to use, you can add it directly to the `PdfRendererBuilder`:

```java
PdfRendererBuilder builder = new PdfRendererBuilder();
builder.useFont(new File("path/to/MyFont.ttf"), "MyFontAlias", 400, BaseRendererBuilder.FontStyle.NORMAL, true);
```

In this example, `"MyFontAlias"` is an alias you can use in your CSS to refer to this font. The `400` represents the font-weight, and `BaseRendererBuilder.FontStyle.NORMAL` is the style of the font. The last parameter `true` indicates whether the font is embedded in the PDF.

### Using a Font Directory

If you have a directory with several fonts, you can add the entire directory, and `PdfRendererBuilder` will make all the fonts in that directory available for use:

```java
builder.useFontDirectory(new File("path/to/font/directory"));
```

### Specifying Fonts in CSS

After you've added fonts to `PdfRendererBuilder`, you can specify which font to use in your HTML/CSS. For example, if you've added a font with the alias `"MyFontAlias"`, you can use it in your CSS like this:

```css
body {
    font-family: 'MyFontAlias', sans-serif;
}
```

Or for Arabic content specifically, you might have:

```css
@font-face {
    font-family: 'MyArabicFont';
    src: url('path/to/MyArabicFont.ttf') format('truetype');
}

body {
    font-family: 'MyArabicFont', sans-serif;
}
```

### Complete Example

Here's how you might put it all together in a method that converts HTML to PDF with a custom font:

```java
private void htmlToPdfWithCustomFont(String inputHtml, String outputPdf, File fontFile) throws IOException {
    try (OutputStream os = new FileOutputStream(outputPdf)) {
        PdfRendererBuilder builder = new PdfRendererBuilder();

        builder.withUri(outputPdf);
        builder.toStream(os);
        builder.useFont(fontFile, "MyFontAlias");
        builder.withHtmlContent(inputHtml, new File(".").toURI().toString());

        builder.run();
    }
}
```

This method assumes you have your HTML content as a `String` and a `File` object pointing to your custom font. It sets up the `PdfRendererBuilder` to use the custom font and then renders the HTML content to a PDF file.

Remember to replace `"path/to/MyFont.ttf"` with the actual path to your font file, and adjust the CSS in your HTML content to use the font as needed.

To generate a PDF with Arabic content using an HTML to PDF library in Java, it's crucial to ensure that the library supports UTF-8 encoding and custom fonts that include Arabic glyphs. Below is a simplified example using the `openhtmltopdf` library, which is capable of handling Arabic content and custom fonts. This example demonstrates how to convert an HTML string containing Arabic text into a PDF document, ensuring the Arabic text is rendered correctly.

### Step 1: Add openhtmltopdf Dependency

First, ensure you have the `openhtmltopdf` library added to your project. If you're using Maven, include the following dependency in your `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.openhtmltopdf</groupId>
    <artifactId>openhtmltopdf-core</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.10</version> <!-- Check for the latest version -->
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.openhtmltopdf</groupId>
    <artifactId>openhtmltopdf-pdfbox</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.10</version> <!-- Check for the latest version -->
</dependency>
```

### Step 2: Prepare Your HTML Content with Arabic Text

Prepare the HTML content you want to convert. Ensure your HTML specifies UTF-8 encoding and uses a font that supports Arabic characters. Here's a simple example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <style>
        @font-face {
            font-family: 'Amiri';
            src: url('path/to/amiri-regular.ttf') format('truetype');
        }
        body {
            font-family: 'Amiri', serif;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p> </p> <!-- "Hello World" in Arabic -->
</body>
</html>
```

### Step 3: Convert HTML to PDF with Arabic Content

Now, use `openhtmltopdf` to convert the HTML content to a PDF file. Ensure you replace `"path/to/amiri-regular.ttf"` with the actual path to the Amiri font or any other font that supports Arabic.

```java
import com.openhtmltopdf.pdfboxout.PdfRendererBuilder;

import java.io.*;

public class HtmlToPdfArabicExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // HTML content with Arabic text
            String htmlContent = "<!DOCTYPE html>" +
                    "<html>" +
                    "<head>" +
                    "<meta charset=\"UTF-8\">" +
                    "<style>" +
                    "@font-face {" +
                    "font-family: 'Amiri';" +
                    "src: url('path/to/amiri-regular.ttf') format('truetype');" +
                    "}" +
                    "body {" +
                    "font-family: 'Amiri', serif;" +
                    "}" +
                    "</style>" +
                    "</head>" +
                    "<body>" +
                    "<p> </p>" + // "Hello World" in Arabic
                    "</body>" +
                    "</html>";

            // Output PDF file path
            String outputPath = "output.pdf";

            // Convert HTML to PDF
            try (OutputStream os = new FileOutputStream(outputPath)) {
                PdfRendererBuilder builder = new PdfRendererBuilder();
                builder.useFastMode();
                builder.withHtmlContent(htmlContent, new File(".").toURI().toString());
                builder.toStream(os);
                builder.run();
            }

            System.out.println("PDF generated successfully!");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

This example demonstrates generating a PDF with Arabic content. Make sure to adjust the paths and possibly the version of `openhtmltopdf` according to your project setup. The Amiri font is used here for its extensive support for Arabic script, but you can replace it with any font that supports Arabic characters.
